# ReviewFlo — Project Context

ReviewFlo helps small business owners request, collect, and manage customer reviews. The platform has three tiers: Free, Pro, and AI. Read this before starting any task.

## Tech Stack

- **Framework**: Next.js (Pages Router — not App Router)
- **Frontend**: React 19, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS
- **Backend**: Serverless API routes in `/pages/api/`
- **Database**: Supabase (PostgreSQL with RLS)
- **Auth**: Supabase Auth (Email/Password + Google OAuth)
- **Email**: Resend (`lib/email-service.ts`)
- **SMS**: Twilio (`lib/sms-service.ts`)
- **Payments**: Stripe (Pro checkout + webhooks; see **Stripe** below)
- **Analytics**: PostHog
- **AI**: Anthropic SDK
- **Image**: Sharp, Canvas, Vercel OG
- **Validation**: Zod

## Stripe (Pro checkout)

- **Routes**: `pages/api/create-checkout-session.ts` (authenticated checkout URL), `pages/api/webhooks/stripe.ts` (`checkout.session.completed` → `businesses.tier`, Stripe IDs)
- **Env (Vercel + `.env.local`)**: `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY`, `STRIPE_PRO_PRICE_ID`, `STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET` — live vs test keys must match the Stripe mode you use
- **Resolved incident (2026-05):** Production “Stripe connection” errors were **`STRIPE_SECRET_KEY` polluted with non-ASCII** (e.g. Cyrillic lookalikes from a bad paste into Vercel). Node `fetch` rejects those header values. **Fix:** delete the env var in Vercel, paste again **only** from Stripe Dashboard (one line, no rich text), redeploy; **rotate** the key if it was exposed anywhere outside Vercel
- **Code guard**: `lib/stripe-env-ascii.ts` (`firstNonLatin1Index`) — fails fast with a clear message instead of an opaque ByteString error

## Directory Structure

```
pages/             # Next.js pages + API routes
  api/             # All serverless API endpoints
  admin/           # Admin dashboard
  [slug].tsx       # Public review collection page
  dashboard.tsx    # Business owner dashboard
  settings.tsx     # Settings/configuration
components/        # React components
lib/               # Utilities & services
  tier-permissions.ts    # Feature gating — always check this
  email-service.ts       # Resend email templates
  sms-service.ts         # Twilio SMS
  supabase.ts            # Supabase client
  google-business-profile.ts
  posthog-provider.tsx
supabase/migrations/     # DB migrations — always add one for schema changes
scripts/           # Utility scripts
public/            # Static assets
```

## Database — Key Tables

| Table | Purpose |
|-------|---------|
| `businesses` | Core account — business name, slug, tier, branding, API keys |
| `review_requests` | Pro/AI: tracks outbound review request emails/SMS |
| `reviews` | Star ratings submitted on public review page |
| `feedback` | Private feedback from 1-4 star submissions |
| `ai_review_drafts` | AI-generated review draft suggestions |
| `ai_review_responses` | AI-generated responses to reviews |

Key `businesses` fields: `tier` ('free' | 'pro' | 'ai'), `slug` (unique public URL), `google_place_id`, `sms_enabled`, `twilio_phone_number`, `stripe_*`, CRM keys.

## Tier Gating

Always check `lib/tier-permissions.ts` before adding any feature. Every API route that touches a tier-gated feature must verify tier server-side — do not rely on frontend gating alone.

```typescript
import { canUseAIFeatures, canUsePro } from '@/lib/tier-permissions'
if (!canUsePro(business.tier)) return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Pro tier required' })
```

## API Route Pattern

All API routes follow the same shape — see `pages/api/send-review-request.ts` as the canonical example:
1. Auth check (Bearer token → `supabaseAdmin.auth.getUser()`)
2. Input validation (trim, return 400 if missing)
3. Business lookup + tier check
4. Do the work
5. Return clean JSON

## Conventions

- **Migrations**: every DB schema change needs a migration file in `supabase/migrations/`. Never alter tables directly.
- **Canonical docs**: `ARCHITECTURE.md` and `QUICK_REFERENCE.md` in the repo root. If these conflict with this rule, those files win — they're more up to date.
- **Public URL**: `usereviewflo.com`
- **Dev server**: `npm run dev` (runs on localhost:3000)
